WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.564 --> 00:00:03.147
(bright music)

2
00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:11.010
<v Speaker>Preoperative testing.</v>

3
00:00:11.010 --> 00:00:13.230
Belinda, take it away. Thank you, ma'am.

4
00:00:13.230 --> 00:00:14.130
<v ->All right, thank you.</v>

5
00:00:14.130 --> 00:00:18.480
We're gonna talk about pre-op.

6
00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:21.150
The only disclosure I have is my husband's a surgeon,

7
00:00:21.150 --> 00:00:24.600
so there are a few discussions at home about this.

8
00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:26.793
But in general,

9
00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:33.240
there are not a lot of questions on the boards over surgery.

10
00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:34.620
And when there are,

11
00:00:34.620 --> 00:00:37.200
they're sort of a hodgepodge of things.

12
00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:40.051
So we're gonna cover kind of a hodgepodge,

13
00:00:40.051 --> 00:00:42.960
and try to cover pretty much everything

14
00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:47.160
that you would probably get on surgery except for the stuff

15
00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:49.350
that's gonna come on the surgical abdomen.

16
00:00:49.350 --> 00:00:54.202
So do not spend a huge amount of your time

17
00:00:54.202 --> 00:00:56.250
going back over this.

18
00:00:56.250 --> 00:00:58.110
I mean, this is the kind of stuff you just,

19
00:00:58.110 --> 00:01:00.600
you can look at it, you got it in your brain,

20
00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:03.990
and you're gonna be able to get those questions on the test.

21
00:01:03.990 --> 00:01:08.160
So everybody gets every procedure except

22
00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:11.989
like in office procedures, simple procedures.

23
00:01:11.989 --> 00:01:14.480
But anything that's going to the OR

24
00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:17.550
or the ambulatory surgery center,

25
00:01:17.550 --> 00:01:20.580
these people should have a preoperative evaluation.

26
00:01:20.580 --> 00:01:22.950
And this is just a preoperative assessment.

27
00:01:22.950 --> 00:01:24.870
So it's mostly the evaluation,

28
00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:26.580
it's your history and physical.

29
00:01:26.580 --> 00:01:29.410
So I'm gonna fall back on that several times in this

30
00:01:29.410 --> 00:01:34.410
because it's not an evaluation with a whole workup

31
00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:38.040
of cardiac workup and labs.

32
00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:41.850
It's your H&amp;P and you're going to decide from that

33
00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:45.303
anything that you actually need to get test-wise.

34
00:01:47.248 --> 00:01:50.220
The other thing on this slide is social support.

35
00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:52.860
You're the one that's gonna know what kind of social support

36
00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:55.590
your patient might need after the surgery.

37
00:01:55.590 --> 00:01:58.350
So the only other time I'm gonna talk about that

38
00:01:58.350 --> 00:02:01.080
is a little geriatric assessment.

39
00:02:01.080 --> 00:02:03.180
So these are the things you're going to be looking at

40
00:02:03.180 --> 00:02:06.150
in the history, the patient's age,

41
00:02:06.150 --> 00:02:09.060
and their indications and their functional capacity,

42
00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:10.805
and whether or not they're obese,

43
00:02:10.805 --> 00:02:14.250
kind of the classic stuff in their history.

44
00:02:14.250 --> 00:02:18.330
You wanna know previous anesthesia issues,

45
00:02:18.330 --> 00:02:19.470
you wanna know their meds

46
00:02:19.470 --> 00:02:21.120
and all the other things they're taking

47
00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:23.010
that they're not supposed to be taking.

48
00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:28.010
And then the real evaluation we're gonna hone in here

49
00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:31.800
is their cardiac status and their pulmonary status.

50
00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:34.230
And then we're gonna talk a little bit about

51
00:02:34.230 --> 00:02:39.230
things like risk of bleeding and risk for anemia.

52
00:02:41.610 --> 00:02:44.100
So you saw a 72-year-old patient with diabetes

53
00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:46.050
and hypertension three months ago.

54
00:02:46.050 --> 00:02:48.219
She was well-controlled on her medications.

55
00:02:48.219 --> 00:02:52.102
She's been in for the last four years.

56
00:02:52.102 --> 00:02:54.660
So she's having cataract surgery

57
00:02:54.660 --> 00:02:56.730
and comes to you for a pre-op evaluation.

58
00:02:56.730 --> 00:02:58.530
What will you order?

59
00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:02.373
EKG, CBC, hemoglobin A1C, or nothing.

60
00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:09.390
Yeah, you bet, nothing.

61
00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:12.510
And this is the question they ask all the time.

62
00:03:12.510 --> 00:03:16.307
So please, cataract, they always ask cataract surgery.

63
00:03:16.307 --> 00:03:18.630
Cataract surgery is low-risk

64
00:03:18.630 --> 00:03:22.020
and doesn't need any preoperative evaluation

65
00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:25.440
as far as cardiac risk goes.

66
00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:27.990
So just a tidbit here.

67
00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:31.200
There are 27 million non-cardiac surgeries

68
00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:33.570
in the United States every year.

69
00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:36.783
And there are about 50,000 post-op MIs.

70
00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:43.470
If you wanna do the math there, it's just under 0.2%.

71
00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:45.960
So it's uncommon.

72
00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:50.370
And it's gonna be most common in the people

73
00:03:50.370 --> 00:03:53.040
that we know are at significant risk for that.

74
00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:54.300
So that's what we're looking for,

75
00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:56.370
the people at significant risk.

76
00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:58.650
But do note that half of the mortality

77
00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:02.250
is because of cardiovascular complications.

78
00:04:02.250 --> 00:04:04.740
So when we're looking at the patient's risk,

79
00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:09.740
it's the risk of the surgery plus the risk of the patient.

80
00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:14.280
So those two things are both important

81
00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:16.923
in order to get your total risk status.

82
00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:20.100
So we're looking at our patient again,

83
00:04:20.100 --> 00:04:22.110
overall status, are they healthy?

84
00:04:22.110 --> 00:04:27.110
Do they have mild disease like hypertension?

85
00:04:27.252 --> 00:04:31.650
Or do they have really severe systemic type

86
00:04:31.650 --> 00:04:35.430
of disease like insulin-dependent diabetes

87
00:04:35.430 --> 00:04:40.263
and they have hypertension and hyperlipidemia and COPD.

88
00:04:40.263 --> 00:04:42.900
And you get the picture.

89
00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:45.060
One of the things you have to know is a MET.

90
00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:47.430
It's a metabolic equivalent.

91
00:04:47.430 --> 00:04:52.430
One MET is the energy it takes for you to sit at rest, okay?

92
00:04:54.480 --> 00:04:57.420
The other thing you have to know is four METs.

93
00:04:57.420 --> 00:05:01.500
It takes four METs for you to climb the stairs out there.

94
00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:02.610
And when you get to the top,

95
00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:04.860
you don't have to sit down and rest.

96
00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:07.230
So you can climb the stairs and keep walking.

97
00:05:07.230 --> 00:05:09.810
If you can do that, you have four METs.

98
00:05:09.810 --> 00:05:13.560
And that's good functional status, believe it or not.

99
00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:14.790
So even if it's not,

100
00:05:14.790 --> 00:05:16.980
it doesn't seem like that great a functional status,

101
00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:18.540
that's the number you have to know.

102
00:05:18.540 --> 00:05:20.553
That's four METs, okay?

103
00:05:21.960 --> 00:05:23.880
So when we're looking at our procedures,

104
00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:28.200
a high risk procedure is an immersion procedure

105
00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:31.920
or some type of cardiovascular type of procedure.

106
00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:35.580
So that includes your peripheral vascular procedures.

107
00:05:35.580 --> 00:05:39.973
Low-risk procedures, breast, cataract,

108
00:05:39.973 --> 00:05:43.830
plastic surgery, endoscopic surgeries,

109
00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:45.210
those are all low-risk.

110
00:05:45.210 --> 00:05:46.740
Everything else falls into

111
00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:50.549
that intermediate risk category, all right?

112
00:05:50.549 --> 00:05:52.680
And it's gonna be really important

113
00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:54.333
when we start stratifying here.

114
00:05:55.680 --> 00:06:00.000
So these are your risks for a major adverse cardiac event.

115
00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.780
That's what MACE is. Major adverse cardiac event.

116
00:06:03.780 --> 00:06:05.765
And if you look down here,

117
00:06:05.765 --> 00:06:08.070
one of the criteria we use

118
00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:10.080
is the revised cardiac risk index.

119
00:06:10.080 --> 00:06:13.830
So everything that's starred is one of those.

120
00:06:13.830 --> 00:06:17.310
And one of those things is if it's a moderate risk procedure

121
00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:19.740
that already gets you one point.

122
00:06:19.740 --> 00:06:21.450
So if it's a moderate risk procedure

123
00:06:21.450 --> 00:06:25.590
and you have either ischemic heart disease, heart failure,

124
00:06:25.590 --> 00:06:28.230
chronic renal failure, insulin-dependent diabetes

125
00:06:28.230 --> 00:06:31.470
or history of a CVA, any of those things,

126
00:06:31.470 --> 00:06:35.490
now you are at elevated risk, okay?

127
00:06:35.490 --> 00:06:37.380
So those are the people you're going to look at

128
00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:38.463
most carefully.

129
00:06:40.110 --> 00:06:42.183
So who gets an EKG?

130
00:06:43.170 --> 00:06:46.680
If you don't have a high risk procedure,

131
00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:51.420
if it's a low-risk procedure, you don't get an EKG.

132
00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:53.047
Unless of course the patient,

133
00:06:53.047 --> 00:06:56.130
it looks like they might have an MI right now in your office

134
00:06:56.130 --> 00:06:58.530
and you should be getting an EKG already, right?

135
00:06:58.530 --> 00:07:02.370
But you're not doing it for the procedure.

136
00:07:02.370 --> 00:07:05.160
So low-risk procedure, no EKG.

137
00:07:05.160 --> 00:07:08.640
High-risk procedure, EKG, right?

138
00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:11.250
So it's only those people with the low-risk procedures

139
00:07:11.250 --> 00:07:13.500
that you need to make a decision about.

140
00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:17.910
And in those patients, if they have good functional capacity

141
00:07:17.910 --> 00:07:20.760
and they don't have a lot of cardiac risk factors,

142
00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:22.830
they don't need an EKG.

143
00:07:22.830 --> 00:07:26.100
But if they have low functional capacity

144
00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:28.710
or significant cardiac risk factors

145
00:07:28.710 --> 00:07:30.420
that we just talked about,

146
00:07:30.420 --> 00:07:32.550
then those people are going to fall into

147
00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:35.520
the EKG category, okay?

148
00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:37.440
Low-risk procedure, no EKG.

149
00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:39.750
High-risk procedure, EKG.

150
00:07:39.750 --> 00:07:42.720
And then you have to make the different, for medium risk,

151
00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:45.033
it depends on the patient.

152
00:07:46.170 --> 00:07:48.360
Good functional capacity, no.

153
00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:50.613
Poor functional capacity, get an EKG.

154
00:07:51.510 --> 00:07:54.420
You are seeing a 72-year-old for a pre-op eval

155
00:07:54.420 --> 00:07:55.950
for knee replacement surgery.

156
00:07:55.950 --> 00:07:58.770
She has well-controlled hypertension, aortic stenosis,

157
00:07:58.770 --> 00:08:01.470
diagnosed with an echocardiogram three years ago,

158
00:08:01.470 --> 00:08:03.000
she's had no other problems.

159
00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.150
Some mild dyspnea on exertion. What should you do?

160
00:08:06.150 --> 00:08:09.210
A pulmonary function test? No further testing?

161
00:08:09.210 --> 00:08:12.183
An echo? Or start on statin therapy?

162
00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:19.920
Very good. An echo.

163
00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:21.930
And they need an echo if they haven't had one

164
00:08:21.930 --> 00:08:24.030
in the last year.

165
00:08:24.030 --> 00:08:27.720
And we'll look through those. So cardiac considerations.

166
00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:30.810
So in most cases,

167
00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:33.270
people with reasonably well-controlled hypertension

168
00:08:33.270 --> 00:08:34.980
can undergo surgery.

169
00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:37.440
The anesthesiologist is gonna manage their hypertension

170
00:08:37.440 --> 00:08:38.940
at the time of the surgery.

171
00:08:38.940 --> 00:08:42.720
But for grade three, you see they're 180 over 110,

172
00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:44.550
that's gonna delay it.

173
00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:46.230
Acute coronary syndrome.

174
00:08:46.230 --> 00:08:49.260
That patient goes to the cardiologist.

175
00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:51.150
That one's straightforward.

176
00:08:51.150 --> 00:08:56.150
And if anybody who's had a recent MI,

177
00:08:56.250 --> 00:08:58.504
you wanna postpone any kind of surgery

178
00:08:58.504 --> 00:09:02.392
for at least four to six weeks.

179
00:09:02.392 --> 00:09:07.020
And you can see here on delaying your surgery,

180
00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:10.140
if you've had a balloon angioplasty, it's two weeks.

181
00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:12.660
30 days if they put in a bare metal stent

182
00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:16.590
and six months if they put in a drug eluting stent.

183
00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:19.983
So try to avoid all other surgeries in those time periods.

184
00:09:21.210 --> 00:09:22.200
For heart failure,

185
00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:25.440
heart failure is a big risk factor for surgery.

186
00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:29.610
And so the patients who are at the greatest risk

187
00:09:29.610 --> 00:09:34.610
have a third heart sound and JVD.

188
00:09:34.800 --> 00:09:35.730
So those are the people

189
00:09:35.730 --> 00:09:38.250
that you wanna look at most carefully.

190
00:09:38.250 --> 00:09:43.250
And anybody who has any new dyspnea or new symptoms

191
00:09:43.620 --> 00:09:45.540
that they're not totally stable,

192
00:09:45.540 --> 00:09:47.553
those people need an echocardiogram.

193
00:09:48.660 --> 00:09:53.660
For valvular disease, anybody who has aortic stenosis,

194
00:09:55.650 --> 00:10:00.330
severe mitral stenosis or aortic or mitral regurge.

195
00:10:00.330 --> 00:10:02.610
So anybody with aortic stenosis,

196
00:10:02.610 --> 00:10:06.370
and then anybody with severe other valvular disease

197
00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:09.693
needs an echo within the last year.

198
00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:15.090
And then obviously if they had an echo six months ago,

199
00:10:15.090 --> 00:10:18.243
but they have new symptoms, then they need a repeat echo.

200
00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:24.620
For arrhythmias, if it's atrial fib and they're stable,

201
00:10:25.380 --> 00:10:28.440
you don't need any eval for those people.

202
00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:30.777
If they have a different arrhythmia,

203
00:10:30.777 --> 00:10:35.253
then they need a cardiology eval.

204
00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:40.950
Right, let's look at radiologic and lab evaluations.

205
00:10:40.950 --> 00:10:45.950
These things we do way too many of. So chest X-rays.

206
00:10:47.220 --> 00:10:49.020
Luckily this has moved a little away,

207
00:10:49.020 --> 00:10:50.880
but all patients used to get a chest X-ray

208
00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:54.300
if they were going to surgery, absolutely not appropriate.

209
00:10:54.300 --> 00:10:58.080
You can see what Choosing Wisely says, don't do it.

210
00:10:58.080 --> 00:11:00.690
So I've given you a number of indications

211
00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:04.323
for chest X-rays in older patients, patients with COPD,

212
00:11:05.670 --> 00:11:08.670
that low functional capacity again.

213
00:11:08.670 --> 00:11:11.820
Patients with heart failure or emergency procedures,

214
00:11:11.820 --> 00:11:14.120
those are the ones who should be getting EKGs.

215
00:11:16.770 --> 00:11:20.400
If your surgery is like really close to the diaphragm,

216
00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:21.750
then you might want to consider it

217
00:11:21.750 --> 00:11:24.198
because that's a patient who's not gonna breathe well

218
00:11:24.198 --> 00:11:26.733
after they come out of surgery.

219
00:11:27.703 --> 00:11:32.703
Patients should be screened for obstructive sleep apnea.

220
00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:36.030
And that's with STOP-BANG, I've given you those there.

221
00:11:36.030 --> 00:11:37.440
They snore, they're tired,

222
00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:40.080
they've been observed to stop breathing.

223
00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:43.230
Elevated blood pressure, BMI, age,

224
00:11:43.230 --> 00:11:47.520
neck circumference is greater than 16 and a male gender.

225
00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:50.820
So if you get five to six of those,

226
00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:54.231
you should be thinking about evaluating,

227
00:11:54.231 --> 00:11:57.840
doing a full evaluation for obstructive sleep apnea.

228
00:11:57.840 --> 00:11:59.400
In most cases,

229
00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:02.640
that's not going to keep them from having their surgery,

230
00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:05.400
but it is important for the anesthesiologist to know

231
00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.710
and people who have obstructive sleep apnea

232
00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:09.690
should bring their equipment

233
00:12:09.690 --> 00:12:12.040
if they're going to be staying in the hospital.

234
00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:15.480
Your patient's a 47-year-old female

235
00:12:15.480 --> 00:12:19.260
who's undergoing a rotator cuff repair after a fall skiing.

236
00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:21.627
She takes lisinopril, hydrochlorothiazide,

237
00:12:21.627 --> 00:12:25.380
atorvastatin and and levothyroxine.

238
00:12:25.380 --> 00:12:27.540
She was seen seven months ago for pap smear

239
00:12:27.540 --> 00:12:29.580
and complained of more frequent heavy menses.

240
00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:32.160
Her TSH, lipids and basic metabolic profile

241
00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:34.680
were all within normal limits seven months ago.

242
00:12:34.680 --> 00:12:36.453
Which labs should you order?

243
00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:42.800
TSH, BMP, CBC and lipids? TSH, BMP, CBC, PT/PTT?

244
00:12:44.435 --> 00:12:47.913
BMP and a CBC? Or no labs are necessary?

245
00:12:53.790 --> 00:12:57.030
Yeah, good, you split in the appropriate places here.

246
00:12:57.030 --> 00:12:59.010
So she doesn't need a PT/PTT.

247
00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:01.140
We have no indication for that.

248
00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:03.235
She doesn't need lipids or TSH.

249
00:13:03.235 --> 00:13:06.600
She had a BMP that was normal.

250
00:13:06.600 --> 00:13:08.970
So why would I think about doing it?

251
00:13:08.970 --> 00:13:12.810
Because she's on lisinopril and hydrochlorothiazide.

252
00:13:12.810 --> 00:13:17.280
And so I've gotta be thinking about her electrolytes.

253
00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:20.280
And why would I consider the CBC?

254
00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:22.800
Because she's told you she's having heavy bleeding.

255
00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:24.060
So you have to think about

256
00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:27.750
is she gonna be at risk for anemia?

257
00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:30.210
So Choosing Wisely says,

258
00:13:30.210 --> 00:13:33.480
do not obtain baseline laboratory studies in patients

259
00:13:33.480 --> 00:13:35.850
without significant systemic disease

260
00:13:35.850 --> 00:13:37.560
undergoing low-risk surgery.

261
00:13:37.560 --> 00:13:39.513
Now notice that's low-risk surgery.

262
00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:45.090
But in general, we order far too many tests.

263
00:13:45.090 --> 00:13:48.780
So we should be ordering tests that we have a reason for.

264
00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:52.170
So you can see all of the ones not routinely recommended.

265
00:13:52.170 --> 00:13:55.470
So in patients, just because we're getting them,

266
00:13:55.470 --> 00:13:56.790
just because we're having surgery

267
00:13:56.790 --> 00:13:58.320
doesn't mean we should be getting tests.

268
00:13:58.320 --> 00:14:03.320
Look at the cost. More than $30 billion annually.

269
00:14:03.600 --> 00:14:05.700
We could do a lot of good with that money.

270
00:14:06.562 --> 00:14:08.340
So laboratory testing.

271
00:14:08.340 --> 00:14:10.553
Your analysis now is only indicated

272
00:14:10.553 --> 00:14:15.420
for high-risk urologic or gynecologic procedures.

273
00:14:15.420 --> 00:14:18.120
Basically you're in that neighborhood working.

274
00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:21.630
A CBC, the Anesthesia Society is now recommending this

275
00:14:21.630 --> 00:14:24.630
for everyone undergoing major surgery,

276
00:14:24.630 --> 00:14:28.569
not like an outpatient type of thing, but major surgery.

277
00:14:28.569 --> 00:14:31.950
But be thinking of people at risk for anemia.

278
00:14:31.950 --> 00:14:34.200
So people with chronic kidney disease

279
00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:36.690
or people who are bleeding a lot.

280
00:14:36.690 --> 00:14:40.053
And if the surgery is expected to have a lot of blood loss.

281
00:14:41.700 --> 00:14:43.860
Electrolyte and creatinine testing, again,

282
00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:46.500
think of those for a, like this patient,

283
00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:51.500
who has a reason to have abnormal electrolytes,

284
00:14:51.528 --> 00:14:56.528
and people who are having kidney types of surgeries

285
00:14:58.661 --> 00:15:01.860
where you might be affecting that.

286
00:15:01.860 --> 00:15:05.880
A1C. This is not the place to be screening for diabetes.

287
00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:08.610
So your patients should have a,

288
00:15:08.610 --> 00:15:10.980
if they haven't had an A1C in the last nine months,

289
00:15:10.980 --> 00:15:13.860
and they have diabetes, then definitely they need an A1C,

290
00:15:13.860 --> 00:15:16.020
not because of the surgery.

291
00:15:16.020 --> 00:15:18.120
Now this is gonna be a controversial thing too,

292
00:15:18.120 --> 00:15:20.640
because a lot of surgeons will not do surgery

293
00:15:20.640 --> 00:15:25.020
if the A1C is not within eight or nine.

294
00:15:25.020 --> 00:15:27.769
They have their own criteria for that.

295
00:15:27.769 --> 00:15:29.820
But what you're really wanting to do

296
00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:32.123
is get their diabetes under control

297
00:15:32.123 --> 00:15:35.760
and A1C is a three-month look back.

298
00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:39.630
So what you wanna do is get their sugars tightly controlled

299
00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:41.790
prior to the surgery.

300
00:15:41.790 --> 00:15:44.400
So that may be a one to two week process

301
00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:46.293
that you do prior to the surgery.

302
00:15:48.450 --> 00:15:53.450
Kidney, in patients with post-op acute kidney injury,

303
00:15:57.540 --> 00:16:00.087
there's a really high mortality rate for these people.

304
00:16:00.087 --> 00:16:02.640
So we wanna make sure that we take anybody

305
00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:06.900
who we know has kidney disease into our surgery

306
00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:09.180
in a maximized state.

307
00:16:09.180 --> 00:16:13.620
And it's pretty impressive how low the GFR can be

308
00:16:13.620 --> 00:16:15.030
that you don't have to worry about it.

309
00:16:15.030 --> 00:16:19.410
You can see clear down to below 15,

310
00:16:19.410 --> 00:16:21.180
those patients do pretty well.

311
00:16:21.180 --> 00:16:22.980
But when you get down into that range,

312
00:16:22.980 --> 00:16:24.840
one of the things you can consider

313
00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:27.690
is actually dialyzing the patient prior to surgery

314
00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:29.703
and optimizing them for the surgery.

315
00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:34.021
Coag tests, I'm gonna give you what you can look at

316
00:16:34.021 --> 00:16:36.360
to decide if you need a coag test.

317
00:16:36.360 --> 00:16:37.703
In most cases you don't.

318
00:16:37.703 --> 00:16:40.710
And then the one test that we should err on the side

319
00:16:40.710 --> 00:16:42.660
of getting more are the pregnancy tests.

320
00:16:42.660 --> 00:16:45.720
Because always nice to know the patient's pregnant

321
00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:47.910
before they go into the surgery.

322
00:16:47.910 --> 00:16:50.040
Okay, here's the bleeding assessment.

323
00:16:50.040 --> 00:16:51.690
It's called the HEMSTOP.

324
00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:55.950
And I would recommend that the easiest way

325
00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:57.660
is just have the patient fill this out.

326
00:16:57.660 --> 00:16:59.370
If they're getting a preop eval,

327
00:16:59.370 --> 00:17:01.170
just have them fill it out.

328
00:17:01.170 --> 00:17:03.270
They have to get two things positive

329
00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:06.603
before you even have to think about getting a PT/PTT.

330
00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:08.855
In children,

331
00:17:08.855 --> 00:17:13.800
most common things we see in children are tonsillectomies

332
00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:16.320
and orthopedic procedures.

333
00:17:16.320 --> 00:17:17.970
There are a couple of really interesting things,

334
00:17:17.970 --> 00:17:20.010
like deciding whether or not the parents

335
00:17:20.010 --> 00:17:22.500
should go back to the pre-op area.

336
00:17:22.500 --> 00:17:26.130
That's gonna be very dependent on the parent-child dyad.

337
00:17:26.130 --> 00:17:28.380
In some cases, it's not a good idea.

338
00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:31.865
In some cases, it can really help the patient.

339
00:17:31.865 --> 00:17:34.980
You should think about things like pregnancy testing

340
00:17:34.980 --> 00:17:36.985
in all your teens.

341
00:17:36.985 --> 00:17:41.985
And asking about and counseling about nicotine secession.

342
00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:48.570
Routine laboratory testing in general, in teens,

343
00:17:48.570 --> 00:17:49.560
you don't need it.

344
00:17:49.560 --> 00:17:52.350
There's just, teens are healthy kids,

345
00:17:52.350 --> 00:17:55.320
unless you have a very specific thing going on in the kid,

346
00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:57.183
they don't need laboratory testing.

347
00:18:00.630 --> 00:18:03.510
Today we're looking at the SARS-CoV as well.

348
00:18:03.510 --> 00:18:06.540
So here are some conditions

349
00:18:06.540 --> 00:18:09.690
that require optimization prior to surgery.

350
00:18:09.690 --> 00:18:10.980
You see there's a whole list of them,

351
00:18:10.980 --> 00:18:13.590
but things like airway anomalies, seizure disorders,

352
00:18:13.590 --> 00:18:16.320
malignancies, Jehovah witnesses.

353
00:18:16.320 --> 00:18:21.320
Make sure that you have in place everything you need

354
00:18:21.812 --> 00:18:24.483
if they do require blood.

355
00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:27.900
Okay, you're caring for a five-month-old child

356
00:18:27.900 --> 00:18:29.220
who developed intussusception.

357
00:18:29.220 --> 00:18:31.290
The mother's still exclusively breastfeeding.

358
00:18:31.290 --> 00:18:34.740
How long must the child fast prior to surgery?

359
00:18:34.740 --> 00:18:37.173
Two hours, four hours, six hours or eight hours?

360
00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:40.373
Thanks.

361
00:18:44.100 --> 00:18:46.890
Actually for breast milk, it's four hours.

362
00:18:46.890 --> 00:18:48.780
So here they are. Clear liquids, two.

363
00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:53.250
Breast milk, four. Formula or light meal is six.

364
00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:56.010
And fatty foods or meats or in general,

365
00:18:56.010 --> 00:18:58.899
you went to Wendy's, now it's eight.

366
00:18:58.899 --> 00:19:02.132
So a lot of times,

367
00:19:02.132 --> 00:19:04.890
the surgeons will tell you it has to be eight hours.

368
00:19:04.890 --> 00:19:08.040
But that is definitely not the case,

369
00:19:08.040 --> 00:19:09.723
and particularly for children.

370
00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:14.010
This is a preoperative eval in older patients,

371
00:19:14.010 --> 00:19:16.860
make sure you're looking at cognitive status.

372
00:19:16.860 --> 00:19:20.700
You know what their goals are, their life goals post-op.

373
00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:22.980
Where do they expect they're going to be?

374
00:19:22.980 --> 00:19:24.930
A depression screen is important.

375
00:19:24.930 --> 00:19:28.770
And then this risk analysis is really helpful here.

376
00:19:28.770 --> 00:19:32.700
A score of 30 will give you whether or not they're frail.

377
00:19:32.700 --> 00:19:35.280
And a score of 40 is very frail.

378
00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:37.680
So these are people that are gonna be very high risk

379
00:19:37.680 --> 00:19:38.513
for you.

380
00:19:38.513 --> 00:19:40.860
And again, what's their social and living situation

381
00:19:40.860 --> 00:19:44.100
that you're gonna have to deal with after the surgery?

382
00:19:44.100 --> 00:19:47.433
Here are some things for risk reduction in general.

383
00:19:48.390 --> 00:19:51.510
Pre and post-op exercise therapy, or physical therapy,

384
00:19:51.510 --> 00:19:54.360
particularly in our older patients, very important.

385
00:19:54.360 --> 00:19:57.930
Make sure you're assessing for delayed skin healing.

386
00:19:57.930 --> 00:20:00.780
So again, we're looking for smoking, diabetes,

387
00:20:00.780 --> 00:20:02.613
obesity, malnutrition.

388
00:20:03.990 --> 00:20:08.130
Look for dental infection. So look in the mouth.

389
00:20:08.130 --> 00:20:10.320
Because it's a great nidus,

390
00:20:10.320 --> 00:20:12.870
it's a great place to put your bacteria

391
00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:15.210
that can come out after the surgery.

392
00:20:15.210 --> 00:20:17.760
So make sure you know whether or not

393
00:20:17.760 --> 00:20:20.010
there's anything going on in the mouth.

394
00:20:20.010 --> 00:20:22.623
And always smoking cessation. Always.

395
00:20:25.290 --> 00:20:29.430
Okay, some things that we need to work

396
00:20:29.430 --> 00:20:31.680
with their medications on a regular basis.

397
00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:35.580
These are your diabetic patients. So what should they take?

398
00:20:35.580 --> 00:20:39.270
They're gonna hold all of their oral medications.

399
00:20:39.270 --> 00:20:43.950
You're going to continue their long-acting insulin.

400
00:20:43.950 --> 00:20:47.280
So if they take their long-acting insulin in the morning,

401
00:20:47.280 --> 00:20:50.100
they're gonna take that in the morning of surgery,

402
00:20:50.100 --> 00:20:51.451
all right?

403
00:20:51.451 --> 00:20:54.510
If you're worried, if they're really tightly controlled

404
00:20:54.510 --> 00:20:56.580
and you're worried that it's really gonna be too much,

405
00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:57.990
then cut the dose.

406
00:20:57.990 --> 00:21:00.570
But don't hold their long acting insulin.

407
00:21:00.570 --> 00:21:04.350
Obviously you're gonna hold all short acting insulins.

408
00:21:04.350 --> 00:21:07.620
Another important thing is the GLPs.

409
00:21:07.620 --> 00:21:10.110
So more and more data is coming out on them.

410
00:21:10.110 --> 00:21:13.830
Remember, they slow gastric emptying.

411
00:21:13.830 --> 00:21:16.440
And so some of these people have food in their stomachs

412
00:21:16.440 --> 00:21:18.030
for long periods of time.

413
00:21:18.030 --> 00:21:19.560
And so you're gonna wanna,

414
00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:22.530
since those medications are a week long medications,

415
00:21:22.530 --> 00:21:25.050
you're gonna wanna stop them at least a week

416
00:21:25.050 --> 00:21:27.210
prior to the surgery.

417
00:21:27.210 --> 00:21:30.540
So there's been a lot of stuff in the literature lately

418
00:21:30.540 --> 00:21:34.260
about patients showing up on GLPs with full stomachs

419
00:21:34.260 --> 00:21:35.700
and vomiting during surgery.

420
00:21:35.700 --> 00:21:38.310
So hold those GLPs.

421
00:21:38.310 --> 00:21:40.950
And then this last thing is very important.

422
00:21:40.950 --> 00:21:43.917
They love this question on boards.

423
00:21:43.917 --> 00:21:48.917
After surgery, where do you keep their glucose? 140 to 180.

424
00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:53.520
Okay? 140 to 180.

425
00:21:53.520 --> 00:21:56.253
They've asked that question over and over again.

426
00:21:57.990 --> 00:21:59.926
Statins, we know statins are good,

427
00:21:59.926 --> 00:22:02.313
they have lots of benefits.

428
00:22:03.720 --> 00:22:08.720
And so anybody who has cardiovascular disease,

429
00:22:09.210 --> 00:22:11.373
if they're not already on a statin,

430
00:22:12.353 --> 00:22:17.010
feel free to start them on a statin prior to surgery.

431
00:22:17.010 --> 00:22:19.590
You can always stop it later if you want to.

432
00:22:19.590 --> 00:22:23.280
If they're on a statin, do not stop it.

433
00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:27.300
There is a plethora of evidence that stopping that

434
00:22:27.300 --> 00:22:28.770
puts them at significant risk.

435
00:22:28.770 --> 00:22:32.310
So they need to take their statin on the day of surgery.

436
00:22:32.310 --> 00:22:33.990
Remember it's fasting,

437
00:22:33.990 --> 00:22:37.533
but you can take your medication prior to surgery, okay?

438
00:22:37.533 --> 00:22:39.273
With a tiny amount of water.

439
00:22:41.250 --> 00:22:45.510
Beta blockers. This has been a controversy on and off.

440
00:22:45.510 --> 00:22:47.520
If patients are on beta blockers,

441
00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:50.550
absolutely continue them through the surgery.

442
00:22:50.550 --> 00:22:54.540
Do not start a beta blocker really within the month

443
00:22:54.540 --> 00:22:56.250
prior to surgery.

444
00:22:56.250 --> 00:22:59.670
And definitely not within the week prior to surgery.

445
00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:02.100
There is a significant increase in morbidity

446
00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:04.860
and mortality for patients who were started on beta blockers

447
00:23:04.860 --> 00:23:06.180
just prior to surgery.

448
00:23:06.180 --> 00:23:10.620
So that's the bottom line on beta blockers.

449
00:23:10.620 --> 00:23:11.880
If you think they're gonna need it,

450
00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:14.190
try to get it in them a month before surgery,

451
00:23:14.190 --> 00:23:17.580
otherwise continue them throughout the surgery.

452
00:23:17.580 --> 00:23:20.790
Aspirin, we've been back and forth on aspirin.

453
00:23:20.790 --> 00:23:23.373
And really, the bottom line is this.

454
00:23:24.243 --> 00:23:28.053
Aspirin really doesn't make that much difference.

455
00:23:29.070 --> 00:23:32.490
But it does increase their risk of bleeding.

456
00:23:32.490 --> 00:23:36.570
And so we're gonna take 'em off their aspirin.

457
00:23:36.570 --> 00:23:41.430
And the one place that we're gonna change that

458
00:23:41.430 --> 00:23:45.090
is patients who are on dual antiplatelet therapy

459
00:23:45.090 --> 00:23:47.340
like they're on clopidogrel and aspirin,

460
00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:49.470
you're gonna have to stop their clopidogrel.

461
00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:52.890
So you are going to continue the aspirin on those patients

462
00:23:52.890 --> 00:23:54.480
through the surgery.

463
00:23:54.480 --> 00:23:58.383
Otherwise we stop the aspirin five to seven days before.

464
00:24:00.630 --> 00:24:01.590
Which of the following is true

465
00:24:01.590 --> 00:24:05.040
regarding coagulant management prior to a right colectomy

466
00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:07.650
of a 65-year-old with hypertension, hyperlipidemia,

467
00:24:07.650 --> 00:24:08.793
and stable AFib?

468
00:24:10.050 --> 00:24:14.910
So remember, it's AFib here. So, I'm gonna make this easy.

469
00:24:14.910 --> 00:24:16.650
The first two are,

470
00:24:16.650 --> 00:24:20.310
we're stopping our apixaban two days prior to surgery.

471
00:24:20.310 --> 00:24:21.143
The last two are,

472
00:24:21.143 --> 00:24:24.180
we're stopping our warfarin two days prior to surgery.

473
00:24:24.180 --> 00:24:26.130
So which of those is correct?

474
00:24:26.130 --> 00:24:28.770
And then A and C are,

475
00:24:28.770 --> 00:24:32.310
we're going to bridge with low molecular weight heparin.

476
00:24:32.310 --> 00:24:34.173
B and D, we're not bridging.

477
00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:39.600
So is the apixaban or warfarin correct?

478
00:24:39.600 --> 00:24:41.400
And are we bridging or not bridging?

479
00:24:46.740 --> 00:24:50.550
Ooh yeah. So this one was a tough one.

480
00:24:50.550 --> 00:24:52.650
You're stopping the apixaban two days before

481
00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:55.320
and you're not bridging, okay?

482
00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:58.173
We don't need to bridge for stable AFib.

483
00:24:59.820 --> 00:25:02.940
These are our people that are at high thrombolic risk.

484
00:25:02.940 --> 00:25:05.430
So these are the people we're going to bridge.

485
00:25:05.430 --> 00:25:07.506
If they have a mechanical heart valve,

486
00:25:07.506 --> 00:25:10.920
a DVT or PE within the last three months,

487
00:25:10.920 --> 00:25:14.790
or if they also have a hypercoagulable state,

488
00:25:14.790 --> 00:25:17.790
they have severe or multiple thrombophilias,

489
00:25:17.790 --> 00:25:21.063
active cancer or a CHADS-VASc score greater than seven.

490
00:25:22.080 --> 00:25:25.800
Okay? So those are the people that are gonna get bridged.

491
00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:28.170
And then I gave you the management for that,

492
00:25:28.170 --> 00:25:30.273
for low molecular weight heparin.

493
00:25:31.200 --> 00:25:34.590
These are medications we wanna stop prior to surgery.

494
00:25:34.590 --> 00:25:38.548
ACEs and ARBs should be held on the day of surgery, okay?

495
00:25:38.548 --> 00:25:42.720
There is a significant amount of hypotension

496
00:25:42.720 --> 00:25:45.900
that occurs when patients take their ACEs or ARBs.

497
00:25:45.900 --> 00:25:49.860
So those are one of the blood pressure medicines we hold.

498
00:25:49.860 --> 00:25:51.840
We're gonna stop all of our anticoagulants.

499
00:25:51.840 --> 00:25:53.280
I've given you how long there.

500
00:25:53.280 --> 00:25:55.680
So different ones are different.

501
00:25:55.680 --> 00:25:59.220
We're gonna stop our NSAIDs, our Cox-2 inhibitors,

502
00:25:59.220 --> 00:26:01.590
most of our diabetes medicines,

503
00:26:01.590 --> 00:26:03.360
we've already talked about that.

504
00:26:03.360 --> 00:26:06.660
Our osteoporosis agents, any hormone therapy,

505
00:26:06.660 --> 00:26:08.940
any biologic agents.

506
00:26:08.940 --> 00:26:11.520
So all of those things we're gonna stop.

507
00:26:11.520 --> 00:26:14.730
Any herbal, please get them off of their herbals

508
00:26:14.730 --> 00:26:16.800
prior to their surgery.

509
00:26:16.800 --> 00:26:18.210
These are the ones we're going to give.

510
00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:21.480
They're gonna get parenteral antibiotics.

511
00:26:21.480 --> 00:26:23.760
You don't have to worry about that. They're gonna get it.

512
00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:25.530
Their long-acting insulins.

513
00:26:25.530 --> 00:26:27.690
Their steroids, if they're on large doses,

514
00:26:27.690 --> 00:26:29.520
continue their regular dose.

515
00:26:29.520 --> 00:26:31.410
Their anti-arrythmic agents,

516
00:26:31.410 --> 00:26:33.780
most of their antihypertensives, their statins,

517
00:26:33.780 --> 00:26:37.890
their H2 blockers, asthma inhalers, neuro/psych,

518
00:26:37.890 --> 00:26:40.560
anti-Parkinson, anti-seizure,

519
00:26:40.560 --> 00:26:44.352
benzos if they're on large doses or they'll withdraw.

520
00:26:44.352 --> 00:26:48.420
